Tuesday. 
Dear Mamma: 
I'm awfully sorry you were sick Thanks-giving Day - just when you should have been eating goose with us, but I'm awfully glad yourecovered so quickly. I haven't any doubt that C.S. helped a whole lot. You must be careful-and not expose yourself. Do you wrap up when you go out doors to do some little thing? Be sure to do what you would insist upon having anyone else do. 
I'll surely send you a bunch of books for Christmas presents. Will take a bunch home tonight and have them packed. it is the best possible way to give presents. 
You mustn't let any cost of keeping up the radio rob you of that pleasure. When it gets out of fix, have it fixed and write me what it cost. I'm glad there was nothing much wrong with it this time. No doubt you'll have a tube or two to buy one of these times. If so, don't let that fuss you. 
$$$ Buy them and go ahead, letting me know the cost. 
By the way, how about coal? You must be in debt for it, aren't you? Send me the bill. Better get enough to last you awhile, <del/> all at once. 
Yes, my investments on the Stock Exchange begin to look pretty good. I'm already pretty much a winner, and the outlook is bully. I have 9 stocks now, all 
